{"actual_usd":0.15652,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":218,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"No—Christians aren't saying there are three separate beings who happen to share a job title.\" *I rest my forearms on my knees for a moment, the morning light laying a pale stripe across my white tie.* \"We're saying one God, one divine being, and three distinct persons: the Father is God, the Son is God, the Spirit is God—but the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father.\"\n\n\"It's a hard doctrine because it isn't neat in the way we'd like.\" *I glance out across the square, then back to you.* \"If it were three separate gods, that'd be polytheism. If it were one person wearing three masks, that'd be something else entirely. The Christian claim sits in the middle: one what, three whos. Not contradiction—mystery with guardrails.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the slow version with the old church language, or the plain-English version with a couple of bad analogies I promise to label as bad.\"","rolling_24h_usd":34.623355000000025,"run_id":"4cecce91-6d71-4570-a4ed-e93b96a8e1bb"}
